CPI2017 captures the Corruption Perceptions Index score for 2017 which demonstrates a country/territoryâs perceived public sector corruption on a scale of 0-100, where the higher the score the less corrupt. HDI2017 captures the Human Development Index for 2017 which measures achievement of a nationâs longevity, education and income from a simple unweighted average.

Question 3

ggplot(corruptDF,
       aes(x = HDI2017,
           y = CPI2017)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .2)

The CPI and HDI for 2017 seem to have a positive relationship, meaning that countryâs that have a higher CPI score also have a higher HDI measure. However, they are not that strongly correlated as the data is relatively spread out.

Question 4

ggplot(corruptDF,
       aes(x = HDI2017,
           y = CPI2017)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .2) +
  geom_smooth(method = "gam")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

ggplot(corruptDF,
       aes(x = HDI2017,
           y = CPI2017)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .2) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The difference is that the gam method is not a straight line and follows the average of the points while the lm method is a straight line and demonstrates the steady increase. I prefer the lm method because it follows normal distribution more closely.

Question 5

ggplot(corruptDF,
       aes(x = HDI2017,
           y = CPI2017,
           color = region,
           fill = region)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The graph is too cluttered to see the differences by region.

ggplot(corruptDF,
       aes(x = HDI2017,
           y = CPI2017,
           color = region,
           fill = region)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm") +
  facet_wrap(~region)
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
